            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> To clarify, the ask is for a compiler option that can be passed to packages to suppress this warning? \r\n\r\nIndeed\r\n\r\n>  is that better than having the package suppress this warning with the usual mechanisms?\r\n\r\nThere are some advantages:\r\n- a warning filter needs to be specific, so we need a number of them. e.g. in numpy we had filters for `dtype` and `ufunc` but not `ndarray`. So in my second example it then required yet another filter.\r\n- filters are global and can be reset. To make test suites reproducible it makes sense to start with `warnings.resetwarnings()` and then add your own filters (this is what numpy's test runner does, which many projects use).\r\n- The Python warnings mechanism has issues (up to Python 3.6 IIRC) with filters that were reset and then re-added, those didn't work.\r\n\r\nIn general, I'd just much prefer to have a single silence flag that can be passed to Cython, because this issue keeps popping up and wastes a lot of time. And I've personally never encountered a single case where it was useful, so I'd rather investigate the first time that does happen rather than every time it's a false alarm.",
